=Maths and Astronomy
Anaxagoras (~500 BC): Moon reflects light of Sun, Sun is star
Hippocrates (~400BC): medicine (diagnosis, prognosis)
Archimedes (~250 BC): Pi value
Eratosthenes (~250 BC): Earth circumference, prime numbers algorithm
Hipparchus (~150 BC): size and distances of Moon and Sun
--
Galen (~200): roman, anatomy
Zhang Heng (~100): polymath
Zhang Zhongjing (~200): medicine
Liu Hui (~250): Pi value
Zu Chongzhi (~500): Pi value (355/113)
Aryabhata (~500): solar and lunar eclipse, Pi value
Brahmagupta (~650) zero and negative numbers
--
Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz (1646-1716): calculus, binary system, mathematical notation (∫, dx)
- Leibniz wheel (1673): calculator
Johann Bernoulli: Brachistochrone curve (1696)
Jacob Bernoulli: Euler's number (compound interest), law of large numbers
Daniel Bernoulli (1700-1782): probability and statistics, Bernoulli's principle (1738)
Leonhard Euler (1707-1783): graph theory, topology, mathematical notation (Σ,i,e,π)
Carl Friedrich Gauss (1777-1855): number theory, magnetism
- Normal distribution (1823)
Georg Cantor
Bernhard Riemann (1826-1866): integral, higher dimensions

=Islamic Golden Age
Al-Khwarizmi (~800): mathematics (algebra, quadratic equations, decimals, Arabic numerals)
